00:04:44,897 --> 00:04:47,537
This is between someone disclosing

114
00:04:47,537 --> 00:04:50,458
confidential information and someone receiving

115
00:04:50,458 --> 00:04:52,158
confidential information.

116
00:04:52,158 --> 00:04:53,598
It comes up in a couple scenarios,

117
00:04:53,598 --> 00:04:56,699
perhaps if you're interviewing a contractor for a job

118
00:04:56,699 --> 00:04:59,380
and you don't want them to be able to disclose info about it

119
00:04:59,380 --> 00:05:01,160
if you don't hire them, and also if you

120
00:05:01,160 --> 00:05:03,060
were making a confidential game pitch

121
00:05:03,060 --> 00:05:06,121
and don't want them to reveal details about the game idea.

122
00:05:06,821 --> 00:05:11,164
So why do we care about one of these agreements? Well, first off, it's the only way to really

123
00:05:11,164 --> 00:05:16,747
protect abstract ideas and mechanics. As a note, these are things that are not protectable

124
00:05:16,747 --> 00:05:22,370
under regular copyright law. It's also a good way to protect trade secrets. That's a type

125
00:05:22,370 --> 00:05:27,513
of IP that covers things like customer lists or pricing models. And finally, it's just

126
00:05:27,513 --> 00:05:32,256
a way to keep certain stuff secret. You know, maybe the launch date or some details about

127
00:05:32,256 --> 00:05:35,158
the main character that you were hoping to save for a marketing splash.

128
00:05:36,637 --> 00:05:41,360
And these can be scary. Just recently, Oculus lost a $500

129
00:05:41,360 --> 00:05:45,742
million verdict in part because they were found to have breached

