called Representations, Warranties, and Indemnities.

253
00:10:55,226 --> 00:10:58,308
Basically, this just means, what are they promising,

254
00:10:58,308 --> 00:11:00,288
and what happens if it's not true?

255
00:11:00,288 --> 00:11:04,010
Specifically, you're gonna wanna make sure

256
00:11:04,010 --> 00:11:06,210
that this is about intellectual property infringement.

257
00:11:06,210 --> 00:11:09,872
They promise that they didn't steal this stuff from Disney,

258
00:11:09,872 --> 00:11:11,692
and if they did and Disney sues you,

259
00:11:11,692 --> 00:11:13,493
they're the one that's on the hook.

260
00:11:13,493 --> 00:11:14,513
The contractor's on the hook.

261
00:11:15,240 --> 00:11:17,782
And that's doubly important because as a developer,

262
00:11:17,782 --> 00:11:20,123
if you do a development agreement for a third party

263
00:11:20,123 --> 00:11:21,564
or you have a publishing agreement,

264
00:11:21,564 --> 00:11:24,045
you're going to end up making this exact same promise

265
00:11:24,045 --> 00:11:25,086
to your publisher.

266
00:11:25,086 --> 00:11:26,286
And it needs to be true.

267
00:11:26,286 --> 00:11:29,168
And finally, sometimes you'll see non-compete

268
00:11:29,168 --> 00:11:32,870
and non-solicitation clauses in one of these.

269
00:11:32,870 --> 00:11:34,231
Some people don't like them.

270
00:11:34,231 --> 00:11:36,252
Some states won't enforce them if they're very broad.

271
00:11:36,252 --> 00:11:37,673
But be aware that they could be there.

272
00:11:39,321 --> 00:11:41,063
So let's move on to development agreements,

273
00:11:41,063 --> 00:11:41,883
which I just mentioned.

274
00:11:41,883 --> 00:11:46,147
This is often between a client

275
00:11:46,147 --> 00:11:47,768
who is paying for development

276
00:11:47,768 --> 00:11:49,770
and the development studio that they're hiring.

277
00:11:51,347 --> 00:11:53,908
It's gonna come up sometimes when a publisher

278
00:11:53,908 --> 00:11:55,930
foots the bill and it's more of a hybrid model,

279
00:11:55,930 --> 00:11:58,591
but more often for indies, they might be hired

280
00:11:58,591 --> 00:12:00,733
just to make some money by say, Cartoon Network.

281
00:12:00,733 --> 00:12:02,614
They want you to make a game.

282
00:12:02,614 --> 00:12:04,775
Okay, great, so why would you need

283
00:12:04,775 --> 00:12:05,776
a development agreement?

284
00:12:05,776 --> 00:12:08,458
Well, because this game could take you a year,

285
00:12:08,458 --> 00:12:10,539
two years to make, and it's gonna ensure

286
00:12:10,539 --> 00:12:12,240
that you get paid while you're doing that.

287
00:12:12,240 --> 00:12:14,562
It's also gonna make sure that you know

288
00:12:14,562 --> 00:12:17,003
exactly how much work you're signing up for.

289
00:12:18,353 --> 00:12:21,734
This is one of the ways that studios go under.

290
00:12:21,734 --> 00:12:23,634
First off, they get a project that ends up

291
00:12:23,634 --> 00:12:25,415
taking twice as long and they don't get paid

292
00:12:25,415 --> 00:12:27,856
a single cent more, which could sink you.

293
00:12:27,856 --> 00:12:30,276
Or I've seen studios go down when they had

294
00:12:30,276 --> 00:12:31,937
a project canceled right in the middle

295
00:12:31,937 --> 00:12:33,537
and they had to fight to get paid

296
00:12:33,537 --> 00:12:35,418
what they were already owed from that project

297
00:12:35,418 --> 00:12:36,718
and they had to look for new work.

298
00:12:38,046 --> 00:12:39,847
So we can avoid this.

299
00:12:39,847 --> 00:12:43,290
First off, a familiar face, intellectual property rights.

300
00:12:43,290 --> 00:12:46,453
In an agreement like this, probably the client

301
00:12:46,453 --> 00:12:48,434
is hiring you to make the game for them.

302
00:12:48,434 --> 00:12:50,536
So they're gonna end up owning the rights.

303
00:12:50,536 --> 00:12:54,499
That's fine, but with two key exceptions.

304
00:12:54,499 --> 00:12:58,082
First off, you don't assign these rights

305
00:12:58,282 --> 00:13:03,365
until you get your final check. And that way you have leverage if they decide that they don't

306
00:13:03,365 --> 00:13:08,707
want to pay you. Which can be very important practically. Another important thing that you

307
00:13:08,707 --> 00:13:14,770
need to have in this section is what's called developer tools. This is an ownership right that

308
00:13:14,770 --> 00:13:21,133
you have and what I would call your special sauce. So basically engines, code libraries,

309
00:13:21,133 --> 00:13:25,315
know-how that you've developed while working on this game that you might use in your own games

310
00:13:25,315 --> 00:13:27,276
in the future or in future projects.

311
00:13:27,777 --> 00:13:31,323
you want to state that the company that you're working for

312
00:13:31,323 --> 00:13:33,968
doesn't get to own this. They get a license and the developer

313
00:13:33,968 --> 00:13:36,993
keeps ownership of this. That way they can never stop you from

314
00:13:36,993 --> 00:13:39,457
using it in the future and in fact they can't even reverse

315
00:13:39,457 --> 00:13:39,978
engineer it.

316
00:13:41,884 --> 00:13:43,466
Next, you want to know how you're getting paid. That's why

317
00:13:43,466 --> 00:13:46,889
you're doing this, right? So you're probably going to get

318
00:13:46,889 --> 00:13:50,373
paid some flat fee for the project, but you want to make

319
00:13:50,373 --> 00:13:53,116
sure that some of that's up front. Ideally 50 percent if you

320
00:13:53,116 --> 00:13:55,719
can swing it. And then you're going to get paid the rest in

321
00:13:55,719 --> 00:13:58,862
milestones as you deliver the content. So first playable

322
00:13:58,862 --> 00:14:00,263
alpha, beta, that sort of thing.

323
00:14:01,108 --> 00:14:04,792
Make sure that there are clear terms as to when you've

324
00:14:04,792 --> 00:14:05,493
delivered.

325
00:14:05,493 --> 00:14:07,875
They can't just sit on it for three weeks and then tell you

326
00:14:07,875 --> 00:14:08,756
they don't like it.

327
00:14:08,756 --> 00:14:09,437
Five days.

328
00:14:09,437 --> 00:14:11,799
And if they don't tell you, then it's deemed accepted.

329
00:14:11,799 --> 00:14:13,081
That's the kind of thing you want.

330
00:14:13,081 --> 00:14:18,286
If there's rev share, make sure we do all the same sort of

331
00:14:18,286 --> 00:14:20,849
math that we did before when we talked about rev share.

332
00:14:20,849 --> 00:14:22,491
You've got to think about those details.

333
00:14:22,945 --> 00:14:26,129
And you also again have to think about scope of work.

334
00:14:26,129 --> 00:14:27,491
This could be a big project.

335
00:14:27,491 --> 00:14:30,274
You need a game design document, tech specs,

336
00:14:30,274 --> 00:14:32,277
that list the features you're developing.

337
00:14:32,277 --> 00:14:33,899
Not just what the features are, but how many.

338
00:14:33,899 --> 00:14:36,963
Are you doing five levels or 50 levels?

339
00:14:36,963 --> 00:14:37,964
Two character models or 20?

340
00:14:37,964 --> 00:14:40,107
That's a big difference.

341
00:14:40,107 --> 00:14:41,809
And to go with this section.

342
00:14:42,249 --> 00:14:46,132
You want a section that allows for what are called change

343
00:14:46,132 --> 00:14:50,174
orders, meaning if they want more stuff outside the scope,

344
00:14:50,174 --> 00:14:53,616
they have to sign an agreement that says they're going to pay

345
00:14:53,616 --> 00:14:54,297
you more money.

346
00:14:54,297 --> 00:14:55,718
You tell them how much it costs.

347
00:14:55,718 --> 00:14:57,719
And if they don't want to sign that, you

348
00:14:57,719 --> 00:14:58,520
don't have to do it.

349
00:14:58,520 --> 00:15:00,701
This prevents what's called scope creep.

350
00:15:00,701 --> 00:15:04,123
And that can be the death of a studio, death by 1,000 cuts.

351
00:15:04,123 --> 00:15:05,544
Clients don't understand game development.

352
00:15:05,544 --> 00:15:07,305
They think it takes two minutes to change something.

353
00:15:07,305 --> 00:15:08,346
Really, it takes two weeks.

354
00:15:08,346 --> 00:15:09,407
So this protects you.

355
00:15:10,492 --> 00:15:14,154
And likewise, you are protected by a good termination section.

356
00:15:14,154 --> 00:15:16,015
You need to be able to get out of a bad deal

357
00:15:16,015 --> 00:15:17,396
if someone is not paying you.

358
00:15:17,396 --> 00:15:19,217
So you should have an ironclad right

359
00:15:19,217 --> 00:15:23,540
to get out of the agreement if you have a late payment

360
00:15:23,540 --> 00:15:25,721
and the right to claim what you're still owed.

361
00:15:26,242 --> 00:15:28,783
Additionally, your client is probably going to want to know

362
00:15:28,783 --> 00:15:32,165
if they can have the right to terminate for convenience.

363
00:15:32,165 --> 00:15:35,287
What this means is essentially they need to stop the project

364
00:15:35,287 --> 00:15:37,328
because match threes aren't hot anymore,

365
00:15:37,328 --> 00:15:39,130
whatever they decide.

366
00:15:39,130 --> 00:15:42,452
That's fine, but you want to make sure that you're going to

367
00:15:42,452 --> 00:15:43,932
get paid a kill fee.

368
00:15:43,932 --> 00:15:46,754
That means they're going to pay you a flat amount that you

369
00:15:46,754 --> 00:15:48,755
agree to, or maybe all of the next milestone.

370
00:15:48,755 --> 00:15:51,337
This gives you a cushion so that you're not caught with no

371
00:15:51,337 --> 00:15:52,718
money when you're looking to find a new

372
00:15:52,718 --> 00:15:53,658
project for the studio.

373
00:15:54,357 --> 00:15:56,959
And finally, I told you you'd see reps and warranties again.

374
00:15:56,959 --> 00:15:59,501
They're definitely going to make sure that you promise the

375
00:15:59,501 --> 00:16:03,184
whole game you deliver is free of infringing material.

376
00:16:03,184 --> 00:16:05,506
And for that to be true, you've got to make sure that

377
00:16:05,506 --> 00:16:07,568
you've signed all those work for hire agreements.

378
00:16:07,568 --> 00:16:10,610
They're also going to make sure that you don't have any

379
00:16:10,610 --> 00:16:12,092
Easter eggs hidden in the game.

380
00:16:12,092 --> 00:16:15,514
They do not like hidden features ever since the GTA 3

381
00:16:15,514 --> 00:16:16,775
hot coffee issue.

382
00:16:16,775 --> 00:16:21,519
So make sure that you disclose this, because you could be on

383
00:16:21,519 --> 00:16:22,860
the hook if there's liability there.

384
00:16:24,472 --> 00:16:27,973
So some practical concerns about development agreements.

385
00:16:27,973 --> 00:16:30,215
If you're not getting paid, don't wait.

386
00:16:30,215 --> 00:16:31,956
Contracts don't enforce themselves.

387
00:16:31,956 --> 00:16:33,236
You need to speak up for yourself

388
00:16:33,236 --> 00:16:35,037
and assert the rights you have.

389
00:16:35,037 --> 00:16:37,399
So give them notice of breach

390
00:16:37,399 --> 00:16:39,900
as soon as they have a late payment.

391
00:16:39,900 --> 00:16:42,461
Stop working, don't do work for free.

392
00:16:42,461 --> 00:16:43,882
And if it's the last payment,

393
00:16:43,882 --> 00:16:44,923
don't hand over the code

394
00:16:44,923 --> 00:16:48,505
until they've given you that final check.

395
00:16:48,505 --> 00:16:52,387
To politely paraphrase one of my fellow lawyers,

396
00:16:52,387 --> 00:16:53,207
F you, pay me.

397
00:16:54,905 --> 00:16:56,926
So let's move on to publishing agreements, which I'm sure

398
00:16:56,926 --> 00:16:57,987
you're all familiar with.

399
00:16:57,987 --> 00:17:00,949
It's between a publisher and a developer

400
00:17:00,949 --> 00:17:01,749
with respect to a game.

401
00:17:01,749 --> 00:17:07,173
These come up basically if the publisher's funded development,

402
00:17:07,173 --> 00:17:09,394
which is sort of the old school AAA model.

403
00:17:09,394 --> 00:17:10,235
You still see that.

404
00:17:10,235 --> 00:17:11,696
And then it's more of a development

405
00:17:11,696 --> 00:17:12,676
publishing agreement.

406
00:17:12,676 --> 00:17:16,739
But a lot of indies end up with a mostly finished game.

407
00:17:16,739 --> 00:17:19,080
And they need a publisher just for things like distribution

408
00:17:19,080 --> 00:17:21,582
or marketing or help with QA and that sort of thing.

409
00:17:22,462 --> 00:17:25,685
So why do we care about a publishing agreement?

410
00:17:25,685 --> 00:17:28,247
Well, if you have a publishing deal,

411
00:17:28,247 --> 00:17:32,971
you want to define how broad the publisher's license is,

412
00:17:32,971 --> 00:17:34,573
how you're getting paid on your game,

413
00:17:34,573 --> 00:17:36,134
because it's your game,

414
00:17:36,134 --> 00:17:39,818
and what exactly the publisher's actually doing for you.

415
00:17:40,990 --> 00:17:42,811
These can easily get scary.

416
00:17:42,811 --> 00:17:45,953
Games can get stuck in limbo with a publisher

417
00:17:45,953 --> 00:17:47,774
that doesn't care about them and no way to get out.

418
00:17:47,774 --> 00:17:51,395
I have had, for example, two clients who both came to me

419
00:17:51,395 --> 00:17:52,616
wanting to get out of publishing deals

420
00:17:52,616 --> 00:17:55,177
with the same publisher.

421
00:17:55,177 --> 00:17:58,319
One of them got out, I sent a single email, took one day.

422
00:17:58,319 --> 00:18:01,840
The other one, it took months and they had to pay a lot.

423
00:18:01,840 --> 00:18:03,741
And the difference was a single sentence

424
00:18:03,741 --> 00:18:05,602
that was in the termination section.

425
00:18:06,386 --> 00:18:09,559
So, let's make sure we know which terms to look out for.

426
00:18:09,559 --> 00:18:11,828
By now, I think you can all guess what is coming first.

427
00:18:12,623 --> 00:18:14,385
IP rights.

428
00:18:14,385 --> 00:18:16,967
You want to make sure, A, that you're not assigning

429
00:18:16,967 --> 00:18:17,868
the rights to your game.

430
00:18:17,868 --> 00:18:20,510
So if you're assigning the copyright, that means you've

431
00:18:20,510 --> 00:18:20,870
sold the game.

432
00:18:20,870 --> 00:18:21,751
They own it now.

433
00:18:21,751 --> 00:18:23,833
And also make sure there aren't any sort of gotchas

434
00:18:23,833 --> 00:18:27,476
where if you're late, they suddenly own your game.

435
00:18:27,476 --> 00:18:29,858
But if it's just a license for them to sell your game,

436
00:18:29,858 --> 00:18:32,020
that's not good enough to say it's a license.

437
00:18:32,020 --> 00:18:34,402
You need to know a lot of things about how broad this is.

438
00:18:34,402 --> 00:18:37,484
So first, how long does that license last?

439
00:18:37,484 --> 00:18:38,105
Forever?

440
00:18:38,105 --> 00:18:38,525
One year?

441
00:18:39,366 --> 00:18:41,669
How broad is it geographically?

442
00:18:41,669 --> 00:18:43,831
You may not want the same publisher in China that you

443
00:18:43,831 --> 00:18:44,712
have in the EU.

444
00:18:44,712 --> 00:18:46,894
They may have different connections.

445
00:18:46,894 --> 00:18:50,718
And then you need to know which platforms it covers.

446
00:18:50,718 --> 00:18:53,061
Does your publisher know anything about mobile?

447
00:18:53,061 --> 00:18:55,523
Then why are they entitled to publish you on mobile?

448
00:18:55,523 --> 00:18:57,645
And finally, and this is huge.

449
00:18:58,266 --> 00:19:00,008
Which products is it covering?

450
00:19:00,008 --> 00:19:01,571
Is it just your game?

451
00:19:01,571 --> 00:19:04,935
Or are we talking about sequels, prequels, DLC?

452
00:19:04,935 --> 00:19:07,018
Or maybe we're even talking about games that you make

453
00:19:07,018 --> 00:19:09,281
later that have nothing to do with this game.

454
00:19:09,281 --> 00:19:12,065
I have seen all of that sneak its way into the IP right

455
00:19:12,065 --> 00:19:13,827
section, so have a close look at that.

456
00:19:14,656 --> 00:19:17,638
Also have a close look at how you are getting paid.

457
00:19:17,638 --> 00:19:20,340
Normally, this is done in a publishing agreement as

458
00:19:20,340 --> 00:19:22,001
revenue share.

459
00:19:22,001 --> 00:19:25,984
You'll see 30-70 in favor of the developer as the standard.

460
00:19:25,984 --> 00:19:27,625
I don't buy that as a standard.

461
00:19:27,625 --> 00:19:31,067
I think that you should argue for every percentage point,

462
00:19:31,067 --> 00:19:33,949
and that they should justify what they're doing for you.

463
00:19:33,949 --> 00:19:36,431
But as it's going to be revenue share, you need to

464
00:19:36,431 --> 00:19:38,472
think about all the things we talked about before.

465
00:19:38,712 --> 00:19:41,473
But you also need to consider one additional key point, which

466
00:19:41,473 --> 00:19:43,694
is recoupable expenses.

467
00:19:43,694 --> 00:19:45,434
So your publisher may say, hey, we're

468
00:19:45,434 --> 00:19:47,855
going to give you an advance to finish the game.

469
00:19:47,855 --> 00:19:50,496
We're going to spend x thousand dollars on marketing.

470
00:19:50,496 --> 00:19:51,396
Great.

471
00:19:51,396 --> 00:19:54,077
But if those are listed as recoupable expenses,

472
00:19:54,077 --> 00:19:57,198
it means they're going to get paid back before you see a cent.

473
00:19:57,198 --> 00:19:59,578
So now your 30-70 split is as, you know.

474
00:20:00,699 --> 00:20:03,962
is 100 zero percent split in their favor and you don't see

475
00:20:03,962 --> 00:20:07,344
money for a while. You can negotiate this and you can make

476
00:20:07,344 --> 00:20:12,769
sure you know which things are recoupable. Next, make sure the

477
00:20:12,769 --> 00:20:16,071
publisher is actually promising to do specific things. I see

478
00:20:16,071 --> 00:20:19,614
this all the time. It drives me nuts. The developer's

479
00:20:19,614 --> 00:20:24,238
obligation section is like one sentence that says we're going

480
00:20:24,238 --> 00:20:25,279
to, you know,

481
00:20:25,419 --> 00:20:28,101
publish and promote the game. That doesn't tell you anything.

482
00:20:28,101 --> 00:20:30,844
They should be telling you how much money they're going to

483
00:20:30,844 --> 00:20:32,605
spend on marketing. And if they're not going to tell you

484
00:20:32,605 --> 00:20:35,168
that, they should be delivering a detailed marketing plan that

485
00:20:35,168 --> 00:20:38,070
you have approval rights over. They should be telling you

486
00:20:38,070 --> 00:20:40,032
things like are they going to be flying you to GDC in packs? Are

487
00:20:40,032 --> 00:20:44,035
they going to put you in the booth? Are they going to pay for

488
00:20:44,035 --> 00:20:46,557
that? How often are they going to put you on the website? You

489
00:20:46,557 --> 00:20:48,799
need to know these things. They should be promising specific

490
00:20:48,799 --> 00:20:51,081
stuff. Because you're giving them your game and they're

491
00:20:51,081 --> 00:20:51,382
taking a cut.

492
00:20:52,051 --> 00:20:53,952
And finally, if they're not doing a good job,

493
00:20:53,952 --> 00:20:55,512
you need an escape hatch.

494
00:20:55,512 --> 00:20:58,533
The termination clause that I talked about before.

495
00:20:58,533 --> 00:21:00,414
Ideally, you want the ability to walk away

496
00:21:00,414 --> 00:21:01,234
with 30 days notice.

497
00:21:01,234 --> 00:21:03,035
But if they're not okay with that,

498
00:21:03,035 --> 00:21:06,536
at least limit the time that they have this license for.

499
00:21:06,536 --> 00:21:09,738
Try them out for a year and then renegotiate.

500
00:21:09,738 --> 00:21:11,298
Or you could ask them to guarantee

501
00:21:11,298 --> 00:21:12,819
a certain amount of revenue per year.

502
00:21:12,819 --> 00:21:13,979
They said they'll make it a hit.

503
00:21:13,979 --> 00:21:16,520
If they can't do a good job, then kick them to the curb.

504
00:21:16,520 --> 00:21:18,501
They shouldn't be your publisher.

505
00:21:18,501 --> 00:21:20,181
Finally, some practical concerns.

